Towards An Adaptive Man-Machine Interface
For
Virtual Environments
Sheila
B.
Banks, Ph.D., Martin
R.
Stytz,
Ph.D., and Eugene Santos, Jr., Ph.D.
Virtual Environments, Human-Computer Interaction,
and
ArtiJcial Intelligence Laboratories
Air Force Institute
of
Technology
sbanks, mswtz, esantos@aft.ajmil
Abstract
We describe an approach to developing
an
adaptive
virtual environment user interface to enable the user to
perform a wide variety of tasks while immersed in the
virtual environment. Currently, virtual environment
operation places an unmanageable cognitive burden upon
the user. While some advances in user interface design
can alleviate some of this problem, the basic problem of
information overload can not be adequately addressed
solely through development of a better interface or
provision of ad hoc decision support tools.
We
contend
that
a
comprehensive design approach to the interface can
improve user access to the virtual environment display
parameters, analysis reports, conferencing and
collaboration capabilities, intelligent agents for user
assistance, motion and orientation controls, recording
devices, and situation awareness aids. Our intelligent
interface research effort, called Symbiotic Information
Reasoning and Decision Support (SIRDS), addresses the
issues related to the design and development
of
an
adaptive, intelligent, leaming man-machine interface.
Construction of the interface requires a mix of traditional
human-computer interaction, data visualization, and
intelligent agents within a software engineering
framework. The framework supports the symbiosis of
human cognition and computational power that is
required to deal with complex virtual environments.
1.
Introduction
A
model virtual environment interface would enable
the user to perform a wide variety
of
useful work without
hindering the user’s observations of the virtual
environment. The interface would provide convenient
access to virtual environment display parameters, analysis
reports, conferencing and collaboration capabilities,
intelligent agents, motion and orientation controls,
recording devices, and situation awareness aids.
The
interface would also allow the user to directly manipulate
objects within the virtual environment and provide means
for the user to perform manipulations using common
interfacemechanisms.
We have begun to address these needs by developing
the Information Pod
[
161 for software architecture, the
Sentinel
[
1
13
for information integration and analysis, and
the Intelligent Interface Agent
(HA)
[4,
51 for
determination of user intent and for intelligent information
presentation.
This
paper reports
on
our progress in
extending the integration of these interface components to
better support user needs. Development of these interface
components was undertaken to support the Synthetic
BattleBridge (SBB) [12] and the Solar System Modeler
(SM)
[
141 virtual environment projects. These projects
use distributed virtual environment (DVE) technology
[13,
IEEE 1278-19931 to insert
a
user into complicated,
purposeful virtual environments.
The next section in this paper provides the necessary
background concerning the projects mentioned above
support
our
DVE adaptive, intelligent interface
requirements. Section Three details the current effort to
inject intelligent agent technology into our user interface
architecture. Finally, Section Four describes future efforts
in the area of intelligent user interfaces and addresses
concluding remarks.
2.
Background
The goal for contemporary immersive virtual
environment interfaces is to support
a
visually rich
environment where information manipulation and display
is facilitated by a variety of mutually supportive, natural
modes of interaction. The user interface supports user
viewpoint movement in any direction and around any axis
and controls the display of the components of the
environment. The interface is usable when using a head-
mounted display (HMD),
or
surround display devices, or
when using a CRT for viewing. The interfacemust also
be easy to modify. Several research teams have
previously addressed parts of this problem. Nielson [7]
describes a set of direct manipulation techniques that use
2D devices to specify a point, translation, and a rotation
around any axis. Robinett and Holloway [9] describe a
system that permits the user to fly through a virtual
world, scale it, and grab objects.
In
their system, the
user’s head and hand are tracked using a magnetic
tracking device, the user views the virtual world through a
HMD and manipulates the world using a dataglove. The
system described by Venolia [17] centers around an
experimental interface that uses a 3D mouse and 3D
interaction techniques. The user places the 3D cursor on
an object with a mouse using visual and acoustic feedback
and can then drag
or
rotate
the
selected object. Cohen
[2]
describes a multimodel user interface that employs both
direct manipulation and language. Sturman, Zeltzer, and
Pieper [IO] describe
a
system for direct manipulation in a
virtual environment. Their system uses a dataglove to
determine user hand postures and a magnetic tracking
device to determine the hand’s location, and permits the
user
to
grasp and manipulate objects in the virtual
environment. Jacob [6] reports the results of his
investigation into the use of eye tracking
to
communicate
user commands to a computer system, which proved

Our work is set within several virtual environment
projects we have underway. Two of these projects are the
Synthetic BattleBridge and the Solar System Modeler.
To place our work
in
context, we will briefly review these
two
projects and the Information Pod user interface used
within these
two
projects.
Figure
1
shows the left panel of the immersed user
interfacein the Synthetic BattleBridge (SBB). The user
is viewing a remote image captured by a virtual camera
and presented on the inset heads-up display (HUD). The
user is tethered to the tank in the foregroundand moves
with it. The image
in
the HUD at the center of the panel
is taken from the airport. Tanks, portrayed as pyramidal
icons, are visible
in
the distance, the railing
in
the
foreground is the railing at the top of the control tower.
The chief objective of the Synthetic BattleBridge
project is to provide a visualization platform for
monitoring and assessing the activities within a DVE.
For the SBB to function as intended it must, at a
minimum, impart a sense of the spatial orientation, type,
motion, and distribution of objects
in
a virtual
environment to the user. Therefore, the SBB allows a
user to move to any location in a virtual environment and
observe the activity without being seen or otherwise
interfering with the activity that is occurring. The system
also allows users to attach to any vehicle and move with
it as though physically attached (or tethered) to it. The
SBB provides these capabilities by computing vehicle
position, motion and velocity data for all actors in the
virtual environment and presenting this information in
real-time using a three-dimensional rendering of the
virtual environment. This unanalyzed information
is
presented to the user using a combination of visual icons
and text. Because unanalyzed information quickly
overwhelms the user, we investigated computer supported
cooperative work
as
a means to lessen information
overload within the virtual environment. We have begun
the process of identifying and building the tools and
supporting technologies that are required
for
effective
cooperation and integrated them into the Synthetic
BattleBridge
[
151.

2:
The User Interface for the Solar System

Figure
2
presents a close-up view of the center panel
in
the Solar System Modeler user interface, showing the
subpanels formotion and orientation control as well as
some Solar System Modeler specific controls. The Moon
is visible to the left of the panel, and the Earth with
orbiting satellites are visible
in
the distance. The Solar
System Modeler is a virtual environment application that
accurately models and visualizes the major components
of
the Solar System, such as comets, planets, moons,
asteroids, and manmade satellites. The
SM
accurately
models satellite orbital motion using published orbital
element descriptions and standard orbital mechanics
models for Earth orbiting and deep-space satellites.
To provide a framework to address the basic recurring
user interface requirements for DVE applications, we
developed the Information Pod user interface
[
161.
The
Pod is a user “capsule” within the virtual world. The
Pod virtually encloses the user, surrounding the user with
2D panels
in
3D space that contain controls and displays.
Each panel
in
the Pod can contain subpanels, with each
subpanel in-turn containing associatively grouped controls
and displays. The controls and displays vary depending
upon the user’s focus of attention and the task
to
be
accomplished. The Pod paradigm allowed us to
fulfill
the
requirements for the system by facilitating solutions to
issues concerning positioning, control, and information
display.
The Pod architecture allows the designer to place
different interface functional categories in different locations
relative to the user and then to factor the specific functions
onto additional subpanels at the primary panel location.
Sub-tasks are identified on the main panel and their
associated subpanel is activated using a button on the
main panel. This approach allows subpanels to be added
to the application without cluttering the Pod‘s display
environment. We use transparent panels because they are
less obtrusive.
Panel activation occurs when the user looks in the
direction of the panel. For each panel
in
the Pod that has
more than one subpanel, the subpanel initially displayed
to
the
user
after
system initialization is the one referenced
the most often in the past. This protocol applies only to
the very first time a panel is activated by a user.
For
91
Authorized licensed use limited to: Thakur College of Engineering and Technology. Downloaded on June 04,2010 at 06:08:26 UTC from IEEE Xplore. Restrictions apply.
subsequent panel activation within a session the subpanel
initially displayed is the last subpanel selected by the
user. On each panel, buttons provide the user with
controls for the Pod. The buttons associated with each
fiinction are grouped into labeled subpanels.
While the Pod and the other tools we have developed
have given the user freedom of motion and access to data
and activity within the DVE, they have also served to
emphasize the need to help the user by locating important
data, highlighting it for the user, and focusing the user on
the relevant aspects of the data. The Sentinel, described
in Section Three, was our first step in this
direction.
However, Sentinel development, while structured, proved
to be too ad hoc and labor intensive.
This realization led
us
to the Symbiotic Information Reasoning and Decision
Support (SIRDS) project.
3.
Symbiotic Information Reasoning and
Decision Support
The current state of operation for users within virtual
environments places an unmanageable cognitive burden
upon the user. The user must attempt to understand the
environment, extract relevant information, and analyze the
information. However, the user’s purpose is typically to
make decisions based upon the relevant information.
Because the information is difficult to locate and has a
short time period of relevance, human decision making
necessarily suffers. While some advances
in
user interface
design, as discussed in the previous section, can alleviate
this problem, the basic problem of information overload
can not be addressed simply through development of a
better interface
or
by using ad hoc decision support tools.
Our goal
is
to develop a comprehensive software
engineering, knowledge engineering, and knowledge
acquisition methodology for Symbiotic Information
Reasoning and Decision Support
(SIRDS).
The name for
the methodology
is
descriptive of our intent. The
interfaceshould be symbiotic, that is work tasks should
be appropriately partitioned between the computer and the
user. The computer looks to the user to provide guidance
and insight into the information that is needed and to
draw complex,
or
high level, inferences from the data.
The user, on the other hand, looks to the computer to
perform data acquisition and management, low level
quantitative and qualitative data analysis, and routine
inference to enable decision support, as well as to manage
the data and
its
display.
A
symbiotic approach is
necessary because the objective is to let the user and the
computer share the taskload; therefore, we use
a
human-
centered approach to task partitioning. In
SIRDS
the key
design question is identifying the aspects of
a
human-
centered task partitioning between the computer and the
human. We will return to this issue below. The
Information Reasoning component of the interface deals
with the issues related primarily to abstracting and
analyzing information. The decision support aspect
of
the
approach relates to the need to enable the user to
understand the relevant data and to perform necessary
analysis to allow the system to provide information
highlighting and user focus of attention activities.
SIRDS requires the development of
an
adaptive,
intelligent, learning human-computer interface.
SIRDS
addresses a wide range of issues, including data fusion,
ambiguity resolution, representational mapping, user
intent inferencing, mixed initiative dialogue, and other
agent and data visualization factors that must be
considered in the formation of a self-consistent, adaptive,
learning interface system.
Construction of the interface
requires a mix of traditional human-computer interaction
techniques, data visualization, and intelligent agents
within a software engineering framework. The framework
supports the symbiosis of human cognition and
computational power that is required to deal with
complex data environments. Intelligent agents are
a
key
aspect of SIRDS, and they perform information fusion,
analysis, and abstraction, as well as deriving information
requirements and controlling information display. These
agents within SIRDS are necessarily of two different
types, one type for the task of reasoning to direct system
data acquisition, assessment, and information synthesis;
and the other for reasoning about information display.
However, the same software architecture and development
methodology is employed to realize both types of agents.
In addition to performing information retrieval and
analysis, SIRDS uses information visualization
techniques to enable the user to understand the derived
information, synthesis operations, and available
processing options. However, to maximize user
effectiveness in an information dense environment,
SIRDS
must operate in anticipation of user information needs.
To
do
so,
SIRDS must first ascertain user information
requirements based on the current situation and a history
of required information. SIRDS then initiates data
retrieval operations and provides focus on and analysis of
the resulting relevant information.
The first step toward realizing this vision is the
development of a design methodology for intelligent
agents for the control of information display and for
assistance in the integration and access to information.
In our view, the development of agents for information
display should be performed in parallel with the design
and development of the traditional aspects of human-
computer interaction and information presentation,
whether the interface be a
2D
or
3D
representation. To be
comprehensive, the methodology must address
information representation and visualization by the
interface agents, the software design of these agents,
usability criteria for agents, and metrics for determining
the necessary agents for interface control.
Our initial
design methodology for intelligent agents for the control
of information display
is
based upon research into
decision networks that incorporate uncertainty reasoning
with previous user performanceand profiles to anticipate
future
user
behavior and needs for information
presentation. These networks employ a general user
support profile and possess the capability to support
92
Authorized licensed use limited to: Thakur College of Engineering and Technology. Downloaded on June 04,2010 at 06:08:26 UTC from IEEE Xplore. Restrictions apply.
specific users by learning information requirements and
refining the general network to accommodate these specific
needs. As user-specific profiles are generated, this
information is used to refine the general-support network.
We believe that this approach is scaleable in breadth
across all interface elements and
in
depth toward ever
smaller units of information.
Initial development in the area of intelligent agents
for information management and display is demonstrated
by our Intelligent Interface Agent (IIA)
[4,
51.
To
effectively predict user intent, an accurate but dynamic
cognitive model of the user is considered to be necessary.
IIA
supports effective user intent prediction by
incorporating the ability to model both the uncertainty
in
user intent and dynamic user behavior within its
knowledge representation. The shortcoming most
cognitive models for intelligent user interfaces is that they
rely on knowledge representations that lack flexibility and
power
in
these two key areas. Employing a knowledge
representation that correctly captures and models
uncertainty
in
human-computer interaction can improve
the modeling of the user and the user interface’s behavior.
One representation that is ideal for representing
uncertainty is Bayesian Networks (BNs)
[I].
A
BN is a
mathematically sound portrayal of uncertainty that models
the probabilistic relationships between items. Bayesian
techniques have attractive properties for developing
interface intelligence because they can capture uncertainty,
which is required to model human intent. Also, Bayesian
techniques are extremely useful
in
predicting future events.
Finally, these techniques are useful for expressing
qualitative relationships (causalities) among beliefs and to
process these relationships in a way that yields intuitively
plausible conclusions.
IIA, which is based upon BNs, uses a model of user
behavior to predict future user behavior, or user intent,
and suggest adaptations. The IIA intelligent agent is a
computer entity that collaborates with and helps a user.
The roles of an intelligent agent include perception of
dynamic conditions in the environment; action to affect
the environment; and reasoning to interpret perceptions,
solve problems, draw inferences, and determine actions.
These intelligent agent roles support the needs of
intelligent user interfaces. For the intelligent agent to
fulfill its roles, it must have the ability to reason. The
reasoning capability is enabled by collecting domain
metrics, transitioning metrics into a representation,
storing information, and inferencing over the stored
information. These actions work together to provide an
environment where the user interface can make intelligent
decisions in support of the user’s intent.
IIA employs a knowledge representation and a
domain metric protocol to manage the intelligence needed
to satisfy the intelligent interface requirements. The basic
knowledge representation for the IIA’s knowledge is a
Bayesian-based
network called the interface learning
network. Because user behavior is not deterministic,
using an uncertainty-based network representation for user
behavior is appropriate. This representation can portray a
large amount of information using a small collection of
interface domain metrics.
An
interface domain metric
collection protocol is the second element of the IIA’s
reasoning ability. Interface domain metrics can be any
type of data that a user interface can collect from the
application domain or the user at runtime. The number
and type of interfacedomain metrics used is solely based
on knowledge required for user interface reasoning.
Information about the application domain can be acquired
from a single interfacedomain metric or combinations of
different types of metrics. The collected interfacedomain
metrics then must be transformed into meaningful
information. In
IIA,
this transformation includes updating
the information maintained
in
the interface learning
network. As a consequence of the continuous update of
domain metric data, when the user interface agent must
make a decision, the agent can draw upon the most recent
knowledge stored
in
the IIA’s network.
The initial design methodology for agents that
perform user-intent based information access and
integration is based upon research
in
decision support
and data abstraction performed while developing the
Sentinel in our lab
[Ill.
The Sentinel ties together
several disjointed data gathering systems to present a clear
and consistent insight into the action within a distributed
simulation space.
The Sentinel project’s goal was to address the
battlespace situation awareness problem by providing an
information consolidation and analysis capability.
Situation awareness at the expert level relies heavily on
skilled memory and on numerous intermediate knowledge
representations
[SI
and can be usefully characterized as a
complex problem solving skill. We have been working
to determine and incorporate the strategies, goals,
subgoals, and skills used by commanders to assess a
battle situation and maintain situation awareness. By
emulating these processes and providing an information
consolidation and analysis capability, each Sentinel gives
the user an indication of the importance of the activity
within its watchspace.
As activity occurs within each Sentinel’s watchspace,
the Sentinel automatically assesses the importance value
of the activity
in
its space and signals this value to the
user. The user is thereby relieved of the necessity of
trying to determine the important areas of the battlespace
from the raw data, initial user assessments are based upon
the ratings provided by the Sentinels since each Sentinel
provides a consolidated assessment
of
the total activity
within its watchspace. Note that the Sentinel does not
make decisions, it consolidates and presents data
in
its
role of a situation awareness aid for the commander. The
Sentinel performs its information aggregation function
using
fuzzy
logic.
To
provide a useful framework for hture
development, the design and implementation
of
SIRDS
systems (including intelligent agents) should be
incorporated into the software engineering lifecycle early
93
Authorized licensed use limited to: Thakur College of Engineering and Technology. Downloaded on June 04,2010 at 06:08:26 UTC from IEEE Xplore. Restrictions apply.
in system development.
By
developing a methodology
for SIRDS and making it explicit early in the software
engineering process, the knowledge gained within our
experimental
VE
domain can be readily transferred to
other information rich, complex domains that require a
SIRDS
capability. This methodology will define a
portion of the software engineering lifecycle that remains
unaddressed.
4.
Conclusions and future work
In this paper we described
an
approach to developing
an adaptive virtual environment user interface to enable
the user to perform a wide variety of tasks while immersed
in the virtual environment. The interface we described
gives the user access to the virtual environment display
parameters, analysis reports, conferencing and
collaboration capabilities, intelligent agents for user
assistance, motion and orientation controls, recording
devices, and situation awareness aids.
The research reported in this article arose
from
the
conviction that virtual environments provide a potentially
revolutionary means for humans to interact with each
other and with computers. However, to achieve this
potential, techniques that allow users to accomplish a
wide variety of work and communication within a virtual
environment must be developed. Our approach to an
adaptive user interface for virtual environments, SIRDS,
provides one means to allow users effective access and use
of the virtual environment and its data. SIRDS has begun
to develop capabilities in
a
wide range of issues including
user intent inferencing, mixed initiative dialogue, data
visualization and information fusion factors that
form
the
basis of a self-consistent, adaptive, learning interface
system for virtual environments.
